%I A397502 #6 Jul 05 2026 22:18:47
%S A397502 6,36,90,150,174,294,378,528,624,804,1014,1254,1470,1740,1974,2244,
%T A397502 2628,3060,3444,3930,4434,4974,5514,6054,6600,7200
%N A397502 Area of the smallest simple polygon (by area) which can be triangulated into n different Pythagorean triangles.
%C A397502 Here polygons are strictly simple, such that all vertices lie on the perimeter of the polygon, no vertex touches more than 2 line segments on the perimeter (as in a degenerate simple polygon, with a fold or enclosing a hole), and no vertex is in the middle of a straightaway.
%H A397502 Charles L. Hohn, <a href="/A397502/a397502.pdf">Example illustration of a(26)</a>
%e A397502 a(1) = 6: a 3,4,5 triangle.
%e A397502 a(2) = 36: a 3,4,5 and a 5,12,13 triangle adjoined at their sides of length 5, in any orientation.
%e A397502 a(3) = 90: 3,4,5, 5,12,13, and 9,12,15, in any orientation.
%o A397502 (PARI) \\ see Hohn link in A396266, using require_primitive_triangles = 0.
%Y A397502 Cf. A396266 (primitive triangles only), A397503 (convex polygons only).
%K A397502 nonn,more,new
%O A397502 1,1
%A A397502 _Charles L. Hohn_, Jun 28 2026
